<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Anchor question</div>
  What story does a landscape tell — and how do you read it like a geologist?
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <p>Unit 2 launches <strong>Thread 4 — Science-Policy-Public</strong>. For the first time, students write for a non-student audience: a hypothetical Greater Chennai Corporation planning meeting. The format choice (≤1500-word written, ≤6-min annotated Google Earth video, or large infographic) is deliberate UDL design — the rubric is identical across all three, so the deliverable assesses landscape-reading thinking, not writing stamina.</p>
  <p>It also continues <strong>Thread 1 — OPVL</strong> with new source types: USGS, Geological Survey of India, ISRO Bhuvan satellite data, historical Google Earth imagery, and Chennai-local news. The geological-time perspective added in Block 3 lets students compare evidence across timescales their U0 + U1 sources never spanned.</p>
  <p>Nine blocks, nine locations, one new AI partner (the <a href="/ai-partners/field-geologist/">Field Geologist</a>). The summative — the <a href="/units/unit-2/assessment-landscape-reading/">Landscape Reading</a> — is the structured biography. The planning-audience share-out in Block 9 is the second defense in the year-long defense arc and the first one with a non-academic audience role.</p>
</div>

<section aria-label="Unit 2 blocks" style="margin-top: 24px;">
  <h2 style="font-size: 22px; color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 12px;">The nine blocks</h2>
  <div class="section-grid">
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-2/block-1/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 1 — Weathering</div>
      <div class="card-desc">How rocks break down. Mechanical vs. chemical weathering, with tropical chemical weathering as the local relevant case. Photo-ID activity on 8 unfamiliar field photos.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-2/block-2/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 2 — Erosion</div>
      <div class="card-desc">How Earth moves itself around. Water / wind / ice / gravity as agents. Marina Beach satellite sequence (2005-2025) as the worked example.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-2/block-3/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 3 — Rivers as Landscape Sculptors</div>
      <div class="card-desc">River systems vocabulary. Cooum + Adyar case study. OPVL practice on three contested sources. Discussion: channelization or restoration?</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-2/block-4/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 4 — Coasts</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Where land meets ocean. Longshore drift, wave erosion, monsoon storms. Marina Beach + Mahabalipuram coast — two coastal stories.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-2/block-5/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 5 — Tropical Landscapes + Chennai Context</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Why tropical landscapes are different (laterites, monsoon sediment cycles). Landscape Reading assigned today; students start considering their location choice.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-2/block-6/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 6 — Field Photo / Map Analysis</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Lock your location. In-class work with Google Earth, historical imagery, and curated photos. Conferencing rotation + peer-check protocol.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-2/block-7/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 7 — Worked Example + OPVL</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Mr. Ignash demos a complete Landscape Reading live. OPVL practice on your primary source. The highest-leverage teacher move of the unit.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-2/block-8/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 8 — Drafting + Peer Feedback</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Full work day on the Landscape Reading. Conferencing rotation. Structured peer feedback round. Final submission format locked.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-2/block-9/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 9 — Share-Out + Unit Close</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Landscape Readings submitted. Class share-out — 3 min + 2 min Q&A each, class plays the planning audience. Unit reflection + connect-forward to U3.</div>
    </a>
  </div>
</section>

